We have to “build up” the cost of goods sold from the cost amounts provided on the sale transactions. In our table the only rows that “affect” cost of goods sold are those having type “Sale” (i.e. revenue sales) that also list a “cost_amount” value. (The other types such as Purchase, Expense, Depreciation, etc. belong to other income‐statement items.)

Now, add these up:

• The 100,000.00 entries appear on 13 sale rows. Their total is:  
  13 × 100,000.00 = 1,300,000.00

• The 1,000.00 entries appear on 7 sale rows. Their total is:  
  7 × 1,000.00 = 7,000.00

• Two rows have 5,000.00 each (one in row 12 and one in row 22):  
  2 × 5,000.00 = 10,000.00

• One row has 20,000.00:  
  20,000.00

Add all these together:  
  1,300,000.00 + 7,000.00 + 10,000.00 + 20,000.00 = 1,337,000.00

Thus the final “Cost of Goods Sold” is 1,337,000.00.
